{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","author_sig":"{\"payload\": \"\", \"payloadType\": \"application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json\", \"signatures\": [{\"keyid\": \"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d\", \"sig\": \"\"}]}","data":{"alias":"illbehaved-girlish-bubblefish","creation_channel":"cli","description":"## Why\n\nGitHub CodeQL flags 28 remaining open code-scanning alerts on `main`: 27 `py/path-injection`\nand 1 `py/stack-trace-exposure`. All are genuine (the false positives were already dismissed\nunder 5b57). They collapse to a small number of root causes:\n\n1. **Unvalidated ticket-id → filesystem path.** `rebar._ids.resolve_ticket_id()` has a fast\n   path that returns the caller's raw string verbatim when it happens to name an existing\n   directory (`_ids.py:152`), *before* any regex/allowlist check. A traversing/absolute id\n   (`../sibling`, `/etc/x`) is handed back as if canonical, then callers join it to the\n   tracker dir. This is the source for ~18 sinks (the reducer read path + `reads.py`).\n2. **Sidecar `resolve_ticket_id(id) or id` fallback.** The audit readers in\n   `completion_sidecar.py` and `plan_review/sidecar.py` fall back to the *raw* id when\n   resolution returns `None`, so even a hardened resolver is bypassed — the raw string builds\n   a `os.path.join(tracker, id)` → `os.listdir`/`open` (sinks 112/119/156/163, 184/192).\n3. **Editor prompt-id traversal.** The workflow editor server's `/prompt?id=` handler builds\n   `<repo>/.rebar/prompts/{pid}.md` from an unvalidated query param (`editor_server.py`\n   158/159); the packaged branch is allowlist-guarded but the project-override branch is not.\n4. **Stack-trace exposure.** The review-bot `/rerun` 502 returns the Gerrit exception string\n   in the response body (`review_bot/app.py:266`).\n\nTrust model: rebar is a single-tenant local tool; the realistic vector is the MCP/CLI\nconfused-deputy (an agent driven by untrusted ticket content passing a crafted id). Severity\nis Low–Medium, but the fixes are low-risk (no legitimate ticket id / prompt id contains a\npath separator, `..`, or is absolute) and retire the whole alert class.\n\n## What\n\nFour containment barriers, mirroring the taint map:\n\n- **`_ids.py`** — add `_is_safe_segment(name)` and reject non-segment ids at the top of\n  `resolve_ticket_id`; rewrite the fast path to normalize + containment-check the candidate\n  against `tracker_dir` and return the directory's `basename` (separator-free by\n  construction). Sanitizes the 18 downstream sinks that build paths from the return value.\n- **`completion_sidecar.py` / `plan_review/sidecar.py`** — drop the `... or ticket_id`\n  fallback in the filesystem-path readers; on `None` return the function's existing empty\n  result (`None`/`[]`/`0`). The hardened resolver's fast path already subsumes the fallback's\n  only legitimate purpose (an id that already names a real dir), so this is behavior-preserving\n  for valid input.\n- **`editor_server.py`** — contain the prompt-id path in `_raw_prompt_text` (resolve +\n  `is_relative_to` the prompts dir) and reject separator-bearing ids at the handler entry.\n- **`review_bot/app.py`** — log the Gerrit exception server-side; return a generic 502 body.\n\nDefault CodeQL query suite unchanged; this is a `src/rebar` change plus new unit tests.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] `resolve_ticket_id` returns `None` for any id that is not a safe single path segment\n      (rejects `../x`, absolute paths, `..`/`.`, `/`/`\\` separators, and leading-dot names),\n      and its fast path returns a separator-free canonical directory name — so no untrusted id\n      escapes the tracker directory. Valid full/short/alias/Jira-key/prefix ids still resolve.\n- [ ] The audit sidecar readers in `completion_sidecar.py` and `plan_review/sidecar.py` no\n      longer fall back to the raw unresolved id; when resolution fails they return their empty\n      result instead of building a filesystem path from unvalidated input.\n- [ ] The workflow editor `/prompt` read (`_raw_prompt_text`) cannot read a file outside\n      `<repo>/.rebar/prompts/`; a traversing prompt id yields no file (returns `None`/404).\n- [ ] The review-bot `/rerun` 502 response body contains no exception/stack-trace text; the\n      detail is logged server-side.\n- [ ] New unit tests assert traversal rejection for the resolver, one sidecar reader, and the\n      editor prompt read, and assert the review-bot 502 body carries no exception detail.\n      `make lint` and the affected test suites pass.","id":"a9d0-ec78-f55e-4e67","parent_id":"","priority":2,"tags":[],"ticket_type":"bug","title":"Harden ticket-id/prompt-id path handling + review-bot error body (retire remaining CodeQL path-injection & stack-trace alerts)"},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"CREATE","timestamp":1784392389478341001,"uuid":"dbe76ace-52e3-4c11-bf8d-a3ff5dcb4824"}